Boil a #pot{} of water with ¼ tsp of @salt{1/4%tsp} for the new potatoes. Chop the @new potatoes{1} into quarters. Chop off the root and the very top of the green leafy part from the @leeks{2}. Slice the leeks in half lengthways and then very, very thinly slice widthways.

Heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add the leeks. Cook them gently for around ~{10%minutes} until soft and sweet. Remove from the heat.

Lay each @British chicken breasts{2} on a #chopping board{} and slice into it from the side. Open it up like a book. You've now butterflied your chicken!

Set your #grill{} to high heat. Rub a little bit of @olive oil{a little} onto each chicken breast. Season with a little pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch} and lay on a #baking tray{}. Place under your grill on the highest shelf for ~{5-6%minutes} on one side. Then take the tray out from under your grill, turn your chicken breasts over and pop back under the grill to cook for another ~{5-6%minutes}.

> The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Whilst your chicken is grilling, add the potatoes to the pot with boiling water, for ~{10%minutes}.

> The potatoes are cooked when you can easily stick a knife through them.

Once they are cooked, drain them.

Crumble the @feta cheese{1} into your cooled leek mixture. Taste the mixture and add a bit of salt and pepper if it needs it.

> Feta is pretty salty already, so make sure you taste as you go to get the seasoning just right.

Spread your leek mixture over the top of your grilled chicken and put back under the grill. Cook for another ~{1-2%minutes} until the top is nice and golden.

Once drained, toss your potatoes in a little @?butter{a little} or some @?olive oil{a little}. Sprinkle over a little @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Finely chop the @mint{2%sprigs}(finely chopped) and sprinkle them over your potatoes too. Serve with your chicken on the side and savour!